In article <1993Jan16.022151.19309@netcom.com> rcain@netcom.com (Robert Cain) writes:
>It is not only possible, it is trivial to spoof any protocol so far
>known that doesn't use shared secrets.

Correction. You don't need shared secrets, only shared,
*authenticated* information that need not be secret (each other's
public keys). This is the big advantage of public key cryptography.

Phil
